transfer pricing system only allows Division B to purchase adaptors from Division A, but Division A has refused to sell more than the current level of adaptors it supplies to Division B.\"", "\"NEW GROUP PURCHASING POLICY\":\"The new group purchasing policy allows Division B to buy adaptors externally, provided that it optimizes the profits of the group as a whole.\"", "\"PROFIT STATEMENT FOR CURRENT POSITION\":\"The profit statement for the current position shows the profit for each division and for The Portable Garage Co (PGC) as a whole, with sales and costs figures split into external sales and inter-divisional transfers.\"", "\"MINIMUM TRANSFER PRICE PER UNIT\":\"The minimum transfer price per unit for any additional adaptors supplied above the current level by Division A to Division B is calculated to ensure Division B can meet its maximum annual demand for the new portable batteries.\"", "\"PHYSICAL CONTROLS\":\"Physical controls should exist to stop unauthorized access to the personal computers that are linked into the servers. Offices should be locked, using keypads or swipe cards, so personnel can only enter the offices where they actually work. This would mean that nurses would not be able to enter the accounts office, for example, unless accompanied by a member of the accounts staff.\"", "\"PERSONNEL CONTROLS\":\"Personnel controls aim to stop employees from deliberately or accidentally compromising security. These may include recruitment of honest individuals, training emphasizing the importance of security, regulations relating to security (such as not allowing staff to share passwords) that are enforced strictly, supervision, and system logs that automatically monitor what employees do while online. These logs may produce exception reports to alert management to unusual activities or repeated attempts to log on with different passwords.\"", "\"FIREWALLS\":\"Firewalls are designed to prevent unauthorized access to the system from outside the organization, especially when the system is connected to the Internet or an intranet.\"", "\"ANTI-VIRUS SOFTWARE\":\"Anti-virus software protects the system from viruses (or malware), which are malicious programs that aim to harm the system or gain access to confidential information. Viruses can be imported into the system by e-mail or by connecting an infected flash drive or other storage device to the system. A particular risk to security is spyware, which watches what users of the system do and then sends the information to a third party (e.g., key logging programs which can be used to discover passwords).\"", "\"REPORTS\":\"Reports should be relevant to the personnel receiving them to avoid information overload. Procedures should be put in place to ensure that reports are only sent to personnel to whom they are relevant. All reports should contain distribution lists, and the people on the distribution list should be asked regularly whether the report is still relevant. Standards should exist for all reports to ensure consistency, such as standard fonts, inclusion of the name of the person who prepared them, page numbers, standard report headers, the date of preparation, and the date of the information on the report. There should also be clear standard definitions of measures used in reports.\"", "\"IMPROVING SECURITY AND INTERNAL DISTRIBUTION PROCEDURES AT ST PEREGRINE'S HOSPITAL\":"], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}